    <h1>Conservation</h1>
</div>
<div data-role="content">
    <ul data-role="listview">
        <li>
            <p>Managing land for arable flowers is very easy. The seeds of some can persist in the soil for years. Providing the right conditions for germination is often all you need. Plants thought to have vanished years ago can come back and flourish! It is also a habitat rich in pollen and nectar providing a vital summer resource for pollinators and other insects. These in turn are eaten by farmland birds and the seeds provide food throughout the winter. Information on the requirements of specific arable plants can be found in the species accounts.</p>
        </li>
    </ul>
