            <h4>Cereal Headlands</h4>
            <img src="images/option_34B.png">

            <p>Some arable flowers, such as <a href="#species/100">shepherds-needle</a> and <a href="#species/94">corn buttercup</a>, will thrive in a situation which mimics historical cropping patterns. These plants can grow within crops as well as along the edges of crops, and can compete with modern cereal varieties that are sown at a reduced drill rate and have less fertiliser.</p>
            <p>Aim to create a widely spaced low-input cereal crop along the field margin:</p>
            <ul class="list-normal-white-space">
                <li>
                    <p>Plough and press the surface. Where required undertake a further surface cultivation, such as disc- or tine-harrowing, or non-inversion techniques using cultivating equipment, for example heavy discs or power harrows. The aim is to create a fine tilth, so that seeds brought to the soil surface can germinate and take root. . Minimum tillage does not disturb the soil surface sufficiently to bring seed to the surface and can leave a green cover, particularly grasses and perennial weeds, which can swamp the margin.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Sow and manage an area of cereal headland. This can be any width but usually between 6-24m.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Sowing a reduced rate of cereal (usually less than 100Kg/ha) can provide optimal crop density allowing arable flowers room between the cereal stalks.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Many arable flowers do not like extremely fertile conditions, and the cereal can take over and shade-out the flowers if it is applied. Under this management it is not advised to fertilise the headland so that the flowers can compete with the cereal crop. Other treatments, such as lime, can also affect the survival of arable plants, and some flowers that like freely-draining soils, particularly sandy soils, may like slightly more acidic soils. The occasional application of lime may be needed to make sure that the soil does not turn too acidic.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Herbicides will kill the arable flowers and shouldn’t be used.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>If the headland is to be harvested, a pre-harvested desiccant could be applied. Unharvested cereal headlands can be left in place over the winter to provide a seed source for farmland birds that will eat both the cereal grain and seeds from the arable flowers.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
