            <h4>Whole Crop Cereals/Roots</h4>
            <img src="images/option_30.png">
            <img src="images/option_32.png">

            <p>Less intensive management of crops on a field scale can also benefit arable flowers. This is particularly suitable where root crops are grown for livestock feed over the winter, such as beet, or spring sown cereals with peas are grown for whole crop silage. Plants that grow in this type of arable habitat include <a href="#species/26">cornflower</a>, <a href="#species/61">corn marigold</a>, <a href="#species/83">weasel’s-snout</a> and <a href="#species/34"> purple bugloss.</a></p>
            <p>Aim to create a field-sized cereal headland under the relevant crop:</p>
            <ul class="list-normal-white-space">
                <li>
                    <p>Plough and press the surface. Where required undertake a further surface cultivation, such as disc- or tine-harrowing, or non-inversion techniques using cultivating equipment, for example heavy discs or power harrows. The aim is to create a fine tilth, so that seeds brought to the soil surface can germinate and take root. . Minimum tillage does not disturb the soil surface sufficiently to bring seed to the surface and can leave a green cover, particularly grasses and perennial weeds, which can swamp the margin.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Sow the desired crop.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Follow a programme of reduced inputs, both fertiliser and lime, across the chosen crop to provide extensive cropping conditions.  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Herbicides will kill the arable flowers and shouldn’t be used.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>

