            <h4>Other</h4>
            <img src="images/option_33.png">

            <p>Areas of un-cropped fallow land under the new Basic Payment Scheme ‘greening’ regulations (as part of Crop diversification and Environmental Focus Areas) can provide suitable conditions for arable flowers.</p>

            <p>Arable flowers are essentially plants of disturbed ground. Other farm activities that provide disturbed ground at the relevant times of year can allow them to flourish.</p>
            <ul class="list-normal-white-space">
                <li>
                    <p>Wild bird seed mixes, grown predominantly to provide winter seeds for farmland birds, can also have a rich arable flora.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Including spring cropping in the rotation can introduce crops with lower inputs that benefit arable flowers.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Summer fallows, used as break crop, can provide a window of opportunity for arable flowers to germinate and set seed.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>Cereal stubbles, particularly those of a spring crop, can provide extended flowering and seeding conditions for later species of arable flowers.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
